  <content-type name="widget_pageMeta">
    <ui:icon>widget</ui:icon>
    <ui:label>Page meta widget</ui:label>
    <ui:description>Page meta widget</ui:description>
    <doc:description xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">
      <p>This widget adds different meta tags with static and dynamic values
        in the page header so that its easy to meet seo and social integration
        requirement, e.g.</p>
      <pre>&lt;meta name="description" content="A very interesting story.."/&gt;</pre>
      <p>
        Both
        <em>Content</em>
        and
        <em>Fallback content</em>
        field supports JSTL
        expressions in the field value. So all the context object set by ECE and WF
        can be used such as: ${article}, ${section}. For instance, the following
        texts can be used as value of
        <em>Content</em>
        and
        <em>Fallback</em>
        fields:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <em>${article.title} in ${section.name}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>${article.fields.leadtext}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>${article.author.name}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>${section.url}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          <em>${publication.name}</em>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>However for some information, where it is difficult to use jstl expressions,
        the widget allows user to use special expressions as following:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Section parameter:
          <em>${sectionParams.</em>
          <i>parameter-name</i>
          <em>}</em>
          E.g. ${sectionParams.section.description}
        </li>
        <li>
          Article tags:
          <em>${meta.articleTags}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          Display image:
          <em>${meta.image.</em>
          <i>representation-name</i>
          <em>}</em>
          E.g. ${meta.image.landscape_80}
        </li>
        <li>
          Gallery images:
          <em>${meta.images[n].</em>
          <i>representation-name</i>
          <em>}</em>
          E.g. ${meta.image[0].landscape_80}
        </li>
        <li>
          Robots meta:
          <em>${meta.searchbot.index} ${meta.searchbot.follow}</em>
        </li>
        <li>
          Keywords:
          <em>${meta.articleKeywords}</em>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>The widget uses following section parameters for adding robot meta tags in the page header:</p>
      <pre>seo.section.allowIndex=true
seo.section.followlinks=true</pre>
      <p>
        If the section parameter for example
        <em>seo.section.allowIndex</em>
        is set to false,
        the section will not be indexed. Besides, all the articles with that section as a home
        section will not be indexed. If the parameter value is not set or true but the article
        field called
        <em>Indexable</em>
        is set to false, the rest would be indexed except that article.
      </p>
    </doc:description>
    <ui:title-field>title</ui:title-field>
    <parameter name="com.escenic.article.staging" value="false" />
    <panel name="general">
      <ui:label>General</ui:label>
      <ui:description>The general fields of meta widget</ui:description>
      <ref-field-group name="basic-widget-fields" />
      <ref-field-group name="pageMeta-widget-metatag-settings-fields" />
    </panel>
    <summary>
      <field mime-type="text/plain" type="basic" name="title">
        <ui:label>Title</ui:label>
        <ui:description>The name of the widget</ui:description>
      </field>
    </summary>
  </content-type>
